[[File:Bishop's House, Iona - geograph.org.uk - 983894.jpg|thumb|Bishop's House, Iona]]
'''Bishop's House''' is a [[Retreat (spiritual)|retreat house]] for the [[Scottish Episcopal Church]], located on the island of [[Iona]], off the west coast of [[Scotland]]. 

==History==
It was built in 1894, when [[Iona Abbey]] was still in ruins, to provide a place for [[Scottish Episcopal Church|Scottish Episcopalians]] on the island. It was originally called Saint Columba's House, after the chapel at its centre dedicated to Saint [[Columba]].<ref>McNeill, p.58</ref> It was established under Bishop [[Alexander Chinnery-Haldane]], [[Bishop of Argyll and The Isles (Episcopal)|Bishop of Argyll and The Isles]] from 1883 to 1906, a year after the tenancy was granted by the [[John Campbell, 9th Duke of Argyll|9th Duke of Argyll]], as a place of "prayer, study, contemplation and Eucharist".<ref name="craft">MacArthur (2002), pp.192,251</ref> Despite protests from the local established church minister the house continued to be supported by the Duke and the Bishop. Thanks to Bishop Chinnery-Haldane’s close involvement with the project, the house became known as the Bishop's House, a title which has stuck.<ref>MacArthur (2002), p.193</ref>

The House was occupied by members of the [[Society of Saint John the Evangelist]] from 1896-1906. Despite the minister's fears they were seeking [[proselyte]]s, they seem to have been more interested in avoiding the roof leaking and finding space for contemplation.<ref name="craft"/> Known locally as "Cowley Fathers", they ran services and held tea parties for the islanders.<ref>MacArthur (1997) pp.46-47</ref> It has since been run as a [[Retreat (spiritual)|retreat house]] for the Scottish Episcopal Church, most recently by their subsidiary group Island Retreats Ltd.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.island-retreats.org/iona.html| title=Bishop's House, Iona| publisher=Island Retreats| accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref>  The Chapel is open to the public and holds two services daily from March to October, and weekly in the winter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.argyll.anglican.org/churches/iona/|title=Iona – St Columba’s Chapel, at Bishop’s House |publisher=Diocese of Argyll and the Isles |accessdate=7 March 2017}}</ref> 

