{{inline|date=February 2017}}
'''Epistemic minimalism''' is the [[epistemology|epistemological]] thesis that mere true belief is [[sufficient condition|sufficient]] for [[knowledge]]. That is, the ''meaning'' of "Smith knows that it rained today" is accurately and completely analyzed by these two conditions:

# Smith believes that it rained today.
# It is true that it rained today.

The thesis is called ''minimalist'' by way of contrast with the competing accounts, which more or less universally require that true belief is [[necessary condition|necessary]] but [[sufficient condition|insufficient]] for knowledge&mdash;that is, that a belief needs to be true in order to count as knowledge, but that truth alone is not enough&mdash;that ''something else'' is needed. Traditionally, that something else was held to be evidential [[Theory of justification|justification]]; today it is usually held to be either justification ''and also'' some other condition, or else some other condition ''instead of'' justification, which will avoid the [[Gettier problem]].

Whatever the analysis, though, the standard view (both pre-Gettier and post-Gettier) pushes for ''narrower'' analyses of knowledge than mere true belief. Epistemic minimalism turns in exactly the opposite direction, and argues for a much more ''inclusive'' analysis--one which includes even Gettier cases, lucky guesses, and completely unjustified beliefs, as long as they happen to be true. The thesis is a ''minimalism'' in the sense that it eschews the additional requirements piled on top of true belief and argues that the intuitive reasons given for the [[justified true belief]] (JTB) analysis and its descendants are either misleading or misunderstood.

The most famous (or infamous) proponent of epistemic minimalism is [[Crispin Sartwell]] (1991). The view has been criticized by many epistemologists, with an influential criticism being delivered by [[William Lycan]] (1994). 

