{{Refimprove|date=May 2017}} {{Infobox religious biography |name = Itsunen Shoyu |image = |caption = |birth name = |alias = |dharma name = |birth_date = 1601 |birth_place = [[Hangzhou]], [[Zhejiang]], [[China]] |death_date = 1668 |death_place = [[Nagasaki, Nagasaki|Nagasaki]], [[Japan]] |nationality = |religion = [[Buddhism]] |school = [[Ch'an]] |lineage = [[Ōbaku]] |title = [[Zen Master|Ch'an master]] |location = |education = |occupation = |teacher = |reincarnation of = |predecessor = |successor = |students = |spouse = |partner = |children = |website = }} '''Itsunen Shoyu''' ({{zh|t=逸然性融}}，1601 in [[Hangzhou]], [[Zhejiang]], [[China]] &ndash; 1668 in [[Nagasaki, Nagasaki|Nagasaki]], [[Japan]]) is famous as a [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] monk and painter who helped to establish [[Zen|Chan]] (Zen) in [[Japan]]. He was also the third abbot of [[Kofukuji (Nagasaki)|Kofukuji Temple]].<ref>[http://kofukuji.com/contents.php?contID=1 縁起/ゆかりの唐僧 ]</ref> In addition to his skill of painting, he also practices the art of [[Seal carving]] and cemented the popularity of this art in Japan.<ref>[http://kofukuji.com/contents.php?contID=1 縁起/ゆかりの唐僧：初期黄檗僧が用いた見事な印章は書を引き立たせ、わが国に篆刻の楽しさ、印章の美しさへの目を開かせた。]</ref>
In 1642 he travelled to [[Nagasaki, Nagasaki|Nagasaki]] as a trader in [[Chinese medicine]], and in 1644 entered [[Kofukuji (Nagasaki)|Kofukuji Temple]], becoming its 3rd abbot in 1645. Established by monks immigrated from China, the temple was then a base of the [[Ōbaku]] school of Zen Buddhism in Japan. In 1654 after multiple requests he succeeded in persuading [[Yinyuan Longqi]] (Ingen Ryuki), the 33rd [[abbot]] of [[Wanfu Temple]] ([[Mount Huangbo]], [[Fujian]]) to emigrate to [[Japan]], where he founded [[Ōbaku (school of Buddhism)|Ōbaku]], the third and final major Japanese [[Zen]] [[Schools of Buddhism|sect]].
Itsunen was a talented late [[Ming Dynasty|Ming]] style painter of Buddhist figural subjects, and is known to have copied works by [[Chen Xian (painter)|Chen Xian]] brought to Japan by [[Yinyuan Longqi]].
