{{Infobox philosopher |region = Western philosophy |era = [[Contemporary philosophy]] |image = |caption = |name = Michael Bratman |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1945|7|25|mf=yes}} |birth_place = |death_date = |death_place = |school_tradition = |main_interests = [[Philosophy of action]], [[Moral Philosophy]] |notable_ideas = intentionality as planning |influences = [[Donald Davidson (philosopher)|Donald Davidson]] |influenced = [[Allan Gibbard]], [[David Velleman]], [[Scott J. Shapiro]] |signature = }}
'''Michael E. Bratman''' (born July 25, 1945) is an American [[philosopher]] who is Durfee Professor in the School of Humanities & Sciences and Professor of Philosophy at [[Stanford University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philosophy.stanford.edu/people/michael-bratman|title=Michael E. Bratman - Philosophy|website=philosophy.stanford.edu}}</ref>
== Biography and career ==
Bratman graduated from [[Haverford College]] in 1967 and earned his Ph.D. in [[philosophy]] at [[Rockefeller University]] in 1974, where he worked with [[Donald Davidson (philosopher)|Donald Davidson]]. He joined the faculty at [[Stanford University]] in 1974, where he has taught ever since.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://philosophy.stanford.edu/sites/default/files/bratman_cv_2015.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2015-08-23 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150620061811/https://philosophy.stanford.edu/sites/default/files/bratman_cv_2015.pdf |archivedate=June 20, 2015 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>
He was elected a Fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.stanford.edu/news/2012/april/aaas-awards-list-041912.html|title=American Academy of Arts and Sciences elects nine Stanford professors to 2012 class of members|publisher=}}</ref> In 2014, [[Oxford University Press]] published a collection of essays on Bratman's work by colleagues and former students, ''Rational and Social Agency: The Philosophy of Michael Bratman.''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://global.oup.com/academic/product/rational-and-social-agency-9780199794515?cc=us&lang=en&|title=Rational and Social Agency: The Philosophy of Michael Bratman|date=May 6, 2014|publisher=Oxford University Press|via=Oxford University Press}}</ref> A review in ''[[Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews]]'' remarked that, "Our very understanding of what it is to form a plan or shared intention is owed in no small part to Michael Bratman's massively influential body of work."<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://ndpr.nd.edu/news/56815-rational-and-social-agency-the-philosophy-of-michael-bratman/|title=Review of Rational and Social Agency: The Philosophy of Michael Bratman|first=Sarah K.|last=Paul|date=March 30, 2015|publisher=|via=Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews}}</ref>
== Philosophical work ==
His interests include [[philosophy of action]] and [[moral philosophy]]. He is best known for his development of the idea that "intention is a distinctive practical attitude marked by its pivotal role in planning for the future."<ref>{{cite book|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2015/entries/intention/|title=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|first=Kieran|last=Setiya|editor-first=Edward N.|editor-last=Zalta|date=March 30, 2018|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|via=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy}}</ref> His work in those areas led him to the [[Belief-Desire-Intention model]] that is used in many areas, including artificial intelligence, today. Bratman's theory of intentions as plans has also led to a distinctive and widely discussed account of "[[collective intentionality]]."<ref>{{cite book|url=https://plato.stanford.edu/archives/sum2013/entries/collective-intentionality/|title=The Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy|first1=David P.|last1=Schweikard|first2=Hans Bernhard|last2=Schmid|editor-first=Edward N.|editor-last=Zalta|date=March 30, 2018|publisher=Metaphysics Research Lab, Stanford University|via=Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy}}</ref>
==Selected bibliography== * {{cite book |first=M. E. |last=Bratman |title=Intention, Plans, and Practical Reason |publisher=[[Center for the Study of Language and Information|CSLI Publications]] |year=1999 |origyear=1987 |isbn=1-57586-192-5 |url=http://csli-publications.stanford.edu/site/1575861925.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060830201118/http://csli-publications.stanford.edu/site/1575861925.html |archivedate=August 30, 2006 |df=mdy-all }} * {{cite book |first=M. E. |last=Bratman |title=Faces of Intention |publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]] |year=1999 |id= 978-0-521-63131-0 |url=http://www.cambridge.org/us/catalogue/catalogue.asp?isbn=0521631319|isbn=0521631319 }}
