[[File:Duncan, William – The elements of logic, 1811 – BEIC 769468.jpg|thumb|''The elements of logic'', 1811]]

'''William Duncan''' (1717 in [[Aberdeen]] &ndash; 1760 in Aberdeen) was a Scottish natural philosopher and classicist, professor of natural philosophy at [[Marischal College, Aberdeen]].

Educated at Marischal College, Aberdeen, he was appointed professor of natural philosophy there in 1752. His popular ''Elements of Logic'', first published in [[Robert Dodsley]]'s ''The Preceptor'' (2 vols, London, 1748), combined a [[John Locke|Lockean]] [[theory of knowledge]] with [[Syllogism|syllogistic]] [[logic]].<ref name=CHECP>{{Citation | last=Haakonssen | first=Knud | year=2006 | contribution=Duncan, William | editor-last=Haakonssen | editor-first=Knud | title=The Cambridge History of Eighteenth-Century Philosophy | publisher=Cambridge University Press | volume=2 | pages=1166}}</ref> He translated the [[Caesar's Commentaries (disambiguation)|Commentaries of Julius Caesar]] and orations of [[Cicero]]; at his death, translations of [[Plutarch]]'s [[Parallel Lives|Lives]] and a continuation of [[Thomas Blackwell (scholar)|Thomas Blackwell]]'s ''Court of Augustus'' were left unfinished.<ref>John Westby-Gibson, [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/823 ‘Duncan, William (1717–1760)’], rev. Patrick Bullard, ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'', Oxford University Press, 2004; online edn, Oct 2009, accessed 6 Dec 2009</ref>

==Works==
